<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<subsection xml:id="ch1-section-calculus-subsection-taylor-series" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Taylor series</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>
            You learned in a calculus course that an infinitely differentiable function <m>f(x)</m>
            can be approximated by<mdash />and sometimes perfectly represented by<mdash />its Taylor series expansion at <m>x=a</m> as given by
        </p>

        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow>f(x) \amp \approx \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \frac{f^{(n)}(a)}{n!}(x-a)^n</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = f(a) + f'(a)(x-a) + \frac{f''(a)}{2}(x-a)^2</mrow>
                <mrow xml:id="eqn-taylor-series" number="yes">\amp \quad + \frac{f^{(3)}(a)}{6}(x-a)^3 + \dots</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <xi:include href="ch1-section-calculus-subsection-taylor-series-subsubsection-approximations.ptx" />

</subsection>